Let's refactor the `customElementName` part a bit.

First off, the `appState.elementType` naming is no longer applicable (it comes from a time where we only had shape tools). Let's rename it to `appState.activeTool` (maybe `selectedTool`, but we have `appState.eraserActive`, so to align. Also `selected*` could get confused with selection).

And since `customElementName` is coupled to `activeTool`, I'm thinking we could make the `appState.activeTool` type into:

```
activeTool: {
  type: typeof SHAPES[number]["value"] | "eraser" | "custom";
  customType?: string
}
```
or better yet:
```
activeTool: 
  | {
    type: typeof SHAPES[number]["value"] | "eraser";
  }
  | {
    type: "custom",
    customType: string
  } 
```

Then we should just expose `setActiveTool(tool: AppState["activeTool"])`.

One downside is it'll make the common case of checking `activeTool` slightly more lengthy, e.g.:

```
if (scene.appState.activeTool.type === "image")
```

Also, since we refer to element types as `type`, we shouldn't name the custom type of `custom` elements as `name`.

